    <h3>SM Series: What Bakers Say</h3>
    <p>The SM-402 and SM-403 are the most popular deck oven models in India's mid-tier bakeries. The double-deck SM-402 hits the sweet spot for bakeries doing 300–600 units of bread per day — enough capacity for a meaningful production run, manageable power consumption, and a price that's accessible for most serious operations. The SM-903 is popular in hotel in-house bakeries and larger commercial operations that need the bigger 60×40 tray format.</p>
    <p>The steam injection on Sinmag deck ovens is widely praised. Unlike some cheaper brands where steam injection is little more than a water drip system that produces inconsistent results, the SM series uses a proper boiler-based steam injection that professional bread bakers consider functional and reliable. It's not quite at Bongard or WP level, but it's far better than what you get from domestic Indian brands.</p>
    <p>One point that bakers frequently mention: the SM series takes about 45–55 minutes to reach baking temperature from cold start. This is typical of firebrick deck ovens, but plan your morning schedule accordingly. Once at temperature, they hold heat very consistently.</p>

    <h2>2. Sinmag Convection Ovens (BC/BN Series): Full Review</h2>
    <p>Sinmag's convection ovens are available in countertop and floor-standing configurations. The BC series is the standard range, and the BN series is the newer enhanced range with better insulation and more programmable controls. In India, the floor-standing models (8-tray and 10-tray) are the most commonly sold.</p>
    <p>Build quality on the convection ovens is solid: stainless steel interior and exterior, double-glazed door glass, and a reversing fan motor that changes direction every few minutes to ensure even heat distribution. This reversal feature is something cheaper ovens often lack, and it makes a real difference for even browning across all tray positions.</p>

